newsitem.title: USA: CBOT soymeal hits 4-month high, soyoil ends mixed.
newsitem.headline: CBOT soymeal hits 4-month high, soyoil ends mixed.

text.p: CBOT soymeal futures closed sharply higher on Tuesday while soyoil ended mixed with strength tied to a late rally in soybeans, traders said.
The March soymeal contract peaked at $242.50 per ton, the highest level since October 2. Traders said stops were hit above a technical resistance point at $237.50.

Trading was very quiet until the last hour of the session when wheat rallied on ideas U.S. wheat exports would pick up amid news of a shipping backlog in Canada. At least 38 vessels were waiting to be loaded at Canadian ports.

Activity was subdued ahead of Wednesday's USDA supply and demand report. Traders anticipated the report would include increases in soybean production estimates for Brazil in Argentina, countered by a cut in U.S. ending stocks.
The market shrugged off reports USDA's attache to Argentina raised the soybean output estimate by 500,000 tonnes to 13.5 million tonnes.
Soymeal ended $5.40 to $3.30 per ton higher with March up $5.40 at $242.10. Soyoil closed 0.10 cent per lb lower to 0.06 higher with March up 0.06 at 23.93.
On the day, R.J. O'Brien and Refco Inc were said to be buyers while Dean Witter was a seller.
Produce Grain was a buyer of March while Cargill Inc was on the sell-side, traders said.
Soymeal volume was estimated by CBOT at 13,000 lots, against Monday's actual volume of 10,051 lots. Soyoil volume was pegged at 8,500 lots against Monday's 8,373 lots.
